The AP shared the data analysis with several climate and data scientists, who all said the conclusion was correct, consistent with scientific peer-reviewed literature and showed a clear sign of human-caused climate change.
However, the first two months of 2019 are showing twice as many cold records than hot ones.
“It’s just been ever warmer.”In between the two cold record days, Pasadena set 145 hot records.
The 1930s, driven by Dust Bowl summers, had about 1.4 hot records for every cold.
“As a measure of climate change, the dailies (temperature records) will tell you more about what’s happening,” said climate scientist Chris Field of Stanford.